2. Basic Statistical Calculations

Following functions are used in basic calculations.

  • mean(): Calculates the average value.
  • median(): Finds the middle value when data is sorted.
  • max() and min(): Identify the maximum and minimum values, respectively.
  • sd(): Computes the standard deviation, a measure of data spread.
  • range(): Returns the minimum and maximum values as a vector.
  • quantile(): Calculates quantiles (e.g., 25th, 50th, and 75th percentiles).
  • summary(): Provides a comprehensive summary, including minimum, maximum, median, mean, and quantiles.
mean(iris_data$Sepal.Length) # mean
## [1] 5.843333
median(iris_data$Sepal.Length) # median
## [1] 5.8
max(iris_data$Sepal.Length)  # max value
## [1] 7.9
min(iris_data$Sepal.Length) # min value
## [1] 4.3
sd(iris_data$Sepal.Length) # standard deviation
## [1] 0.8280661
range(iris_data$Sepal.Length) # range
## [1] 4.3 7.9
quantile(iris_data$Sepal.Length) # quartiles
##   0%  25%  50%  75% 100% 
##  4.3  5.1  5.8  6.4  7.9
summary(iris_data$Sepal.Length) # mean, median, mode, max, min and quantiles. 
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   4.300   5.100   5.800   5.843   6.400   7.900


Interquartile Range

IQR(iris$Sepal.Length)
## [1] 1.3

IQR is the difference between the 75th and 25th percentiles. It is a robust measure of data spread.

3. Using the dplyr package for easy calculation.

The dplyr package is a part of tidyverse


Central Tendency

iris |>
  summarize(
    mean_value = mean(Sepal.Length),
    median_value = median(Sepal.Length),
    count_value = n()
  )
##   mean_value median_value count_value
## 1   5.843333          5.8         150
  • mean(Sepal.Length): Computes the average of the Sepal.Length column.
  • median(Sepal.Length): Finds the middle value of Sepal.Length when sorted.
  • n(): Counts the total number of observations in the dataset.
  • summarize(): Summarizes the dataset with the calculated values. (Both %>% and |> operators achieve the same results. Stick to one for consistency. %>% is superior to |> in some of the tasks. )


Similarly for Petal.Length

iris %>% 
  summarise(
    mean_value = mean(Petal.Length),
    median_value = median(Petal.Length),
    count_value = n()
  )
##   mean_value median_value count_value
## 1      3.758         4.35         150


Grouped Analysis by Species

iris %>% 
  group_by(Species) |> 
  summarise(
    mean_value = mean(Petal.Length),
    mode_valye = median(Petal.Length),
    count_value = n()
  )
## # A tibble: 3  4
##   Species    mean_value mode_valye count_value
##   <fct>           <dbl>      <dbl>       <int>
## 1 setosa           1.46       1.5           50
## 2 versicolor       4.26       4.35          50
## 3 virginica        5.55       5.55          50
  • group_by(Species): Groups the dataset by the Species column.

## 6     6     5       19.7         19.7
## 7     8     3       15.0         15.2
## 8     8     5       15.4         15.4

group_by(cyl, gear): Groups the dataset by both the cyl (number of cylinders) and gear (number of forward gears) columns. Each unique combination of cyl and gear creates a subgroup.

Dispersion and Variability

iris %>% 
  summarise(
    max_value = max(Sepal.Length),
    min_value = min(Sepal.Length),
    standard_deviation = sd(Sepal.Length), # how far the data is deviated from the mean
    variance = var(Sepal.Length)  # how far the data is from the mean
  )
##   max_value min_value standard_deviation  variance
## 1       7.9       4.3          0.8280661 0.6856935
  • max(Sepal.Length) and min(Sepal.Length): Find the maximum and minimum values of Sepal.Length.
  • sd(Sepal.Length): Computes the standard deviation, indicating the average amount by which the values deviate from the mean.
  • var(Sepal.Length): Calculates the variance, the square of the standard deviation, which measures the spread of the data.
  • Comment: The square root of variance is standard deviation. The larger the value, the greater the spread of the data.


Range

range_value = max(iris$Sepal.Length) - min(iris$Sepal.Length)

This calculates the range as a single value (difference between max and min).


4. Quartile Values

quantile(iris$Sepal.Length, probs = c(0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1))
##  25%  50%  75% 100% 
##  5.1  5.8  6.4  7.9
  • quantile(): Calculates quartiles or percentiles of the data.
  • probs: Specifies the probabilities for the desired quartiles:
  • 0.25: First quartile (Q1).
  • 0.50: Median (Q2).
  • 0.75: Third quartile (Q3).
  • 1.00: Maximum value.


Quartile Calculation by Species

iris |> 
  group_by(Species) |>
  summarise(
    Q1 = quantile(Sepal.Length, probs = 0.25),
    Median = quantile(Sepal.Length, probs = 0.5),
    Q3 = quantile(Sepal.Length, probs = 0.75)
  )
## # A tibble: 3  4

## 1 setosa      4.8     5     5.2
## 2 versicolor  5.6     5.9   6.3
## 3 virginica   6.22    6.5   6.9

6. Skewness and Kurtosis

Skewness: Measures the asymmetry of the data distribution. A skewness of 0 indicates a symmetric distribution, negative values indicate left-skewness, and positive values indicate right-skewness.

Kurtosis: Indicates the tailedness of the data. A kurtosis value of 3 typically represents a normal distribution. Values greater than 3 indicate heavy tails, and values less than 3 indicate light tails.

Calculation.

# Install and load the moments package
library(moments)

# Calculate skewness and kurtosis for Sepal.Length
iris %>%
  summarise(
    skewness_value = moments::skewness(Sepal.Length),
    kurtosis_value = moments::kurtosis(Sepal.Length)
  )
##   skewness_value kurtosis_value
## 1      0.3117531       2.426432

Explanation:

  • moments::skewness(Sepal.Length): Calculates the skewness of the Sepal.Length column.

  • moments::kurtosis(Sepal.Length): Computes the kurtosis of the Sepal.Length column.

  • The summarise() function ensures that the results are presented in a summarized format.

  • In moments::skewness(), :: is used to fetch the function of the pakage moments. Similarly, if we want to fetch the select() function of dplyr package, we use dplyr::select().

8. Using ggplot2 for Data Visualization

ggplot2 is part of the tidyverse collection of R packages and is a powerful library for creating advanced and aesthetic visualizations. It follows the grammar of graphics, which involves mapping data to visual properties (aesthetics) and adding geometric objects (geoms) to represent data points.


A. Histogram with ggplot2

ggplot(
  data = iris,
  aes(
    x = Sepal.Length
  )
) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.1,  fill = "skyblue", color = "darkblue") +  # Binwidth determines bar width
  geom_line(stat = "bin", binwidth = 0.1, color = "red", size = 1) +
  labs(
    title = "Histogram of Sepal Length",
    x = "Sepal Length",
    y = "Frequency"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()
## Warning: Using `size` aesthetic for lines was deprecated in ggplot2 3.4.0.
##  Please use `linewidth` instead.
## This warning is displayed once every 8 hours.
## Call `lifecycle::last_lifecycle_warnings()` to see where this warning was
## generated.

  • aes(x = Sepal.Length): Maps Sepal.Length to the x-axis.
  • geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.1): Creates a histogram with bin width of 0.1. The bin width controls the grouping of data points.
  • geom_line(stat = "bin", binwidth = 0.1): Adds a red line representing the bin counts, making trends clearer.
  • theme_bw(): Changes the plots theme to a clean, black-and-white layout.


B. Density Plot

# Overall density
ggplot(
  data = iris,
  aes(x = Sepal.Length)
) +
  geom_density(fill = "green", alpha = 0.7)+
  theme_classic()

  • geom_density(): Creates a smoothed density plot of Sepal.Length.
  • fill = "green": Fills the density curve with green.
  • alpha = 0.7: Adds transparency to the fill. 1 = opaque and 0 = transparent.
  • theme_classic(): provides clean background with x and y lines.


C. Study species-specific distributions with color-coded density plots:

ggplot(
  data = iris,
  aes(
    x = Sepal.Length,
    fill = Species
  )
) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.6) +
  labs(
    title = "Density Plot of Sepal Length by Species",
    x = "Sepal Length",
    y = "Density"
  ) +
  theme_void()

theme_void() gives nothing but graph and its legend.


D. Scatterplot

ggplot(
  data = iris, 
  aes(
    x = Sepal.Length,
    y = Petal.Length
  )
) +
  geom_point(
    aes(color = Species)
  )+
  theme_minimal()

  • aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Petal.Length): Maps Sepal.Length to the x-axis and Petal.Length to the y-axis.
  • geom_point(aes(color = Species)): Creates a scatterplot with points colored by Species.
  • theme_minimal(): Yet another default theme present in ggplot2 package.


E. Boxplot

ggplot(
  data = iris,
  aes(
    x = Species,
    y = Sepal.Length,
    fill = Species
  )
) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  geom_jitter(
    width = 0.3,
    alpha = 1
  )

  • geom_boxplot(): Creates a boxplot for Sepal.Length grouped by Species.
  • The box shows the median, interquartile range (IQR), and potential outliers.
  • geom_jitter(width = 0.3): Adds scattered data points around the boxplot to display data distribution.
  • width = 0.3: Controls the spread of jitter points.
  • alpha = 1: Sets the transparency of the points (fully opaque in this case).
